{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bac292e3-cb83-423c-b30f-920841d21c82","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on Kubernetes:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### To copy the trace off the pod:\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Alternative: `dotnet-counters` for quick triage\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\nThis gives real-time CPU %, GC, thread pool stats — useful before committing to a full trace.\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool install` fails due to no SDK in the container, you can download the standalone `dotnet-trace` global tool from [NuGet](https://www.nuget.org/packages/dotnet-trace) or bake it into your container image.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"53f3e6d3-1053-4151-9ced-04f10d0c499e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a troubleshooting/diagnostic question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":436,"requestId":"C880:1E4705:1D77E50:209363F:6A0524AF"},"id":"f132141b-78f2-4b46-a51a-8f0d4c75974c","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:26:17.478Z","parentId":"a326dacf-869a-4686-b8ed-a262fda82f63"}
